	<item>
		<title>By: David Walker</title>
		<link>http://markos.gaivo.net/blog/?p=598&#038;cpage=1#comment-228828</link>
		<dc:creator>David Walker</dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 29 Mar 2011 11:30:12 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://markos.gaivo.net/blog/?p=598#comment-228828</guid>
		<description>Hi Marko,

This is an interesting conundrum you raise. While Facebook integration does make it easy for people to &quot;sign up&quot; to certain websites, the website owner does not get that user&#039;s registration details which is important in terms of keeping them informed of site updates, marketing messages etc.

You said: &quot;If you are building years long relationship like I have with Amazon, does it really matter if you get me to fully sign-up after third month instead of first?&quot;

I would probably argue that yes it does matter from an income point of view because then Amazon have lost out on potentially two months worth of marketing opportunities. If you are an avid customer of Amazon, they could have sold you a lot more products!

David</description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Hi Marko,</p>
<p>This is an interesting conundrum you raise. While Facebook integration does make it easy for people to &#8220;sign up&#8221; to certain websites, the website owner does not get that user&#8217;s registration details which is important in terms of keeping them informed of site updates, marketing messages etc.</p>
<p>You said: &#8220;If you are building years long relationship like I have with Amazon, does it really matter if you get me to fully sign-up after third month instead of first?&#8221;</p>
<p>I would probably argue that yes it does matter from an income point of view because then Amazon have lost out on potentially two months worth of marketing opportunities. If you are an avid customer of Amazon, they could have sold you a lot more products!</p>
<p>David</p>
